Germany, Year Zero
May 8th always reminds me of the year 1945. Because the end of the war in Europe was really a decisive moment in my life.
When the first Soviet soldiers arrived in our little street, in the western suburbs of Berlin, we knew that the great massacre was coming to an end.
My father, a resistance fighter, would return from the Brandenburg prison.
I would no longer have to hide as I did after my release from a Gestapo camp at the beginning of February.
It was the beginning of a new life.
But first, there was chaos.
With the Nazis gone, the occupying powers had not yet established an administration.
We looted the stores in the neighborhood. I still have some volumes of romantic poetry recovered from a bookstore.
I was sixteen years old. The occupying armies committed all sorts of excesses.
It was difficult to obtain food.
My father was directly transported from his prison to the center of Berlin, and tasked with setting up - from nothing - the city's energy supply office.
For a while, there was no electricity, no transportation, no organized life.
Defeat or liberation?
For the Germans it was a delicate question, even though for our family it was obviously a liberation in every sense of the word.
But for what purpose?
For what future?
“You must help,” my mother told me.
I therefore offered my services to the local Soviet authorities and participated in the distribution of basic food supplies to several distribution points in our Zehlendorf district.
Five weeks later, I was back at school.
I had a special card labeled "victim of fascism," while others wore a Iron Cross obtained for late services rendered to the army.
Some were refugees from the East, many had seen their homes destroyed by bombings, almost all mourned the loss of loved ones.
Yet, this phase did not last.
It is practically unbelievable, but three years later, a monetary reform and liberal policies triggered the "economic miracle" in Germany.
Or more precisely, the West German economic miracle.
The differences between the occupying powers were striking.
In the Soviet zone, progress was slow and mainly accompanied by a new form of subjugation.
Concentration camps like Buchenwald continued to operate, with different guards and prisoners.
On the other hand, after a short period of non-fraternization, the Western powers adopted a policy of controlled reinforcement of autonomy.
One year after the end of the war, there were local administrations, and two years after that, elections.
Democracy was not just an empty word, and it was based on German traditions.
Certainly, not everything was benevolence on the part of the occupying powers.
It was also the beginning of the Cold War, and everyone wanted to consolidate "their" part of Germany.
But there are nevertheless lessons to be learned from this process.
Two lessons in particular deserve to be mentioned.
The first is economic, and linked to the Marshall Plan.
It may be regrettable, but democracy takes root more easily in a context of economic recovery.
For this, above all, there needs to be initiative, from individuals willing to end a period of distress.
These initiatives can be encouraged by policies (such as those of Ludwig Erhard, father of the "social market economy" in Germany), but things are easier with an initial capital.
Hence the importance of American support through the Marshall Plan.
The same way, the European Union has helped formerly communist countries, and continues to support them in their endeavor.
The other lesson, of a moral nature, is more difficult.
The Nuremberg trials made the guilt of Nazi leaders undeniable.
However, Germany did not embark on its long journey by worrying about the past.
In fact, many have described the Adenauer years after 1949 as a period of "restoration," because too many minor Nazi personalities remained in their positions.
In a way, the country ignored its past in order to move forward toward the future.
Years later, after the establishment of a market economy and a political democracy, Germany faced its past, with much success.
The Nazi past is unique in its horror, and comparisons with other traumatized countries therefore lead to confusion.
Yet, in its own way, Poland followed a similar path after 1989: first novelty, then an attempt to confront the past.
In the end, it is a better method.
In Europe, May 8th, 2005 is an opportunity to look back on the past with sadness and anger, but also to turn toward the future, proud of the achievements of the last few decades and therefore filled with hope.
